<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-311-408  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 311 408.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  April 3 1990 v4 n13 p67(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Court dismisses bulk of Xerox suit; Xerox to appeal ruling inApple suit.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Said, Carolyn.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>A US district court judge threw out five of six counts againstApple lodged by Xerox over unfair competition.andP;  The judge basedhis decision on technical and procedural flaws in the presentationrather than similarities between the Apple Lisa and MacintoshFinder and Xerox's Star computer system.andP;  Xerox used a number ofunusual legal grounds rather than claiming straightforward copyright infringement because the statute of limitations had run outon the 10-year-old case.andP;  Xerox will appeal the decision, but onlyafter the final count has been decided.andP;  The final count, whichclaims that Xerox is 'reasonably apprehensive' that Apple will suethe company and its licensees, does not include any request fordamages.andP;  Even if Xerox were to win, there would be no monetaryaward.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Xerox Corp. (cases)Apple Computer Inc. (cases).andO;Ticker:    AAPL; XRX.andO;Topic:     Court CasesLegal IssuesCompetitionCopyright.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Xerox to appeal  ruling in Apple suitandM;By Carolyn SaidandM;San Francisco -- Most of the lawsuit that took Xerox Corp. nearly a decade tofile was dismissed with dispatch by a federal judge here late last month.andM;U.S.andP;  District Judge Vaughn Walker threw out five of six counts in Xerox's$150 million suit.andP;  Filed in December 1989, the suit charged Apple withunfair competition and was an attempt to cancel Apple's copyrights on theLisa and Macintosh Finder on the grounds that they duplicate portions ofXerox's 1981 Star computer system.andM;Apple counsel greeted their victory with elation.andP;  &quot;The whole worldunderstands Apple did a magnificent job of creating a highly original work,&quot;said Jack Brown, lead counsel for Brown andamp; Bain, Apple's law firm.andM;&quot;We welcome the ruling in every way,&quot; Brown added, calling it &quot;a sound, wiseand just decision.&quot;andM;Xerox said it plans to appeal the decision.andP;  &quot;This ruling does not mean thatApple has not taken substantial portions of Star and claimed them as itsown,&quot; the Stamford, Conn.-based company said in a prepared statement.andP;  &quot;Thecourt merely held -- we believe erroneously -- that Xerox did not havestanding to present facts in support of that contention.andP;  We think thedecision is incorrect in the law and we intend to appeal as soon as we areable to do so.&quot;andM;Lawyers said Xerox would not be able to file its appeal until the judge hasdecided the remaining count, which is slated to be heard in 150 days.andM;Since Xerox did not seek damages from Apple in that count, even if Xeroxwins, the victory would be slight, lawyers said.andM;In the remaining count, Xerox claimed that it is &quot;reasonably apprehensive&quot;that Apple may sue Xerox and its licensees.andP;  The count also asks the court toaffirm Xerox's ownership of the Star registration, something that Apple doesnot contest.andP;  Xerox has 30 days to present evidence supporting its claim.andO;The matter will return to court after an additional 120 days for both sidesto prepare arguments.andM;Legal experts agreed that Walker's dismissal of the five counts rested not onthe merits of the case, but on technical and procedural flaws in Xerox'slegal arguments.andM;Rather than straightforwardly claiming copyright infringement -- for whichthe statute of limitations has run out -- Xerox pressed its suit on anassortment of unusual legal grounds.andM;&quot;Novel legal theories are not frequently greeted with enthusiasm by judges,&quot;said Ron Laurie, a Menlo Park, Calif.-based attorney specializing in computerlaw.andP;  &quot;You have to have a case or a controversy [to sustain a suit].andP;  Withoutthe legal skeleton of a copyright-infringement case, the arms and legs of theunfair-competition charge fell off.&quot;andM;Walker dismissed Xerox's request that the Lisa and Macintosh Finderregistrations be struck down.andP;  &quot;Xerox does not have standing to invalidateApple's copyright,&quot; the judge ruled.andM;He also threw out charges of unfair competition and allegations that Appleunjustly enriched itself with products copied from Xerox.andO;</TEXT></DOC>